"Yom-Tov Y., Geffen E.","Recent spatial and temporal changes in body size of terrestrial vertebrates: Probable causes and pitfalls",2011,"Biological Reviews","86","2",,"531","541",,,10.1111/j.1469-185X.2010.00168.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79954461478&partnerID=40&md5=1436accfd2c4dbfe52b693d14559aebb","Department of Zoology, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel","Yom-Tov, Y., Department of Zoology, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel; Geffen, E., Department of Zoology, Tel Aviv University, Tel Aviv 69978, Israel","Geographical and temporal variations in body size are common phenomena among organisms and may evolve within a few years. We argue that body size acts much like a barometer, fluctuating in parallel with changes in the relevant key predictor(s), and that geographical and temporal changes in body size are actually manifestations of the same drivers. Frequently, the principal predictors of body size are food availability during the period of growth and ambient temperature, which often affects food availability. Food availability depends on net primary productivity that, in turn, is determined by climate and weather (mainly temperature and precipitation), and these depend mainly on solar radiation and other solar activities. When the above predictors are related to latitude the changes have often been interpreted as conforming to Bergmann's rule, but in many cases such interpretations should be viewed with caution due to the interrelationships among various environmental predictors. Recent temporal changes in body size have often been related to global warming. However, in many cases the above key predictors are not related to either latitude and/or year, and it is the task of the researcher to determine which particular environmental predictor is the one that determines food availability and, in turn, body size. The chance of discerning a significant change in body size depends to a large extent on sample size (specimens/year). The most recent changes in body size are probably phenotypic, but there are some cases in which they are partly genetic. © 2010 The Authors. Biological Reviews © 2010 Cambridge Philosophical Society.","Bergmann's rule; Birds; Body size; Climate change; Food availability; Global warming; Mammals","animal; bird; body size; climate change; mammal; physiology; review; time; Animals; Birds; Body Size; Climate Change; Mammals; Time Factors; Aves; Mammalia; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Andersen, T., Wiig, O., Growth of the skull of Norwegian lynx. (1984) Acta Theriologica, 29, pp. 89-110; Baker, K.L., Morphometric differentiation in New Zealand populations of the house sparrow (Passer domesticus). (1980) Evolution, 34, pp. 638-653; Baker, A.J., Moeed, A., Rapid genetic differentiation and founder effect in colonizing populations of common mynas (Acridoteres tristis). (1987) Evolution, 41, pp. 525-538; Baldwin, S.P., Kendeigh, S.C., Variations in the mass of birds. (1938) Auk, 55, pp. 416-467; Becker, R.A., Chambers, J.M., Wilks, R.A., (1988) The new S language., , Wadswarth and Brooks, Pacific Grove, California; Blem, C.R., Avian energy storage. (1990) Current Ornithology, 7, pp. 59-113; Blois, J.L., Feranec, R.S., Hadly, E.A., Environmental influences on spatial and temporal patterns of body-size variation in California ground squirrels (Spermophilus beecheyi). (2008) Journal of Biogeography, 35, pp. 602-613; Blondel, J., Coping with habitat heterogeneity: the story of Mediterranean blue tits. (2007) of Ornithology, 148 (SUPPL. 1), pp. S3-S15. , Journal; Both, C., Van Turnhout, C.A.M., Bijlsma, R.G., Siepel, H., Van Strien, A.J., Foppen, R.P.B., Avian population consequences of climate change are most severe for long-distance migrants in seasonal habitats. (2010) Proceedings of the Royal Society B, 277, pp. 1259-1266; Calder, W.A., (1984) Size, function and life history., , Dover Publications, Mineola, NY; Chamaille-Jammes, S., Massot, M., Arago, P., Clobert, J., Global w